Part 2¶

"De-fault Words" in Our Stars:¶

Theme Extraction through Clustering of n-starred Amazon.com product reviews¶

I. Executive Summary¶

Amazon.com is a technology company that has revolutionized commercial trade through its e-commerce platform. It has consistently been at the forefront of innovation through its disruption of well-established industries. Amazon’s key differentiator is its company wide attention to Customer Service. Part of this approach is ensuring that complete and reliable product information is readily available to its customers through customer reviews. These reviews guide shoppers in their purchase decisions as they learn from fellow customers. To reduce time going through reviews, could customer reviews be filtered further according to common themes per n-star rating? This project aims to determine themes from customer reviews corresponding to its star rating as seen in the amazon.com product review section.

Product id's and corresponding star ratings were scraped and mined from a dataset of over 12,000 unique product reviews. These reviews were pre-processed, and vectorized using Term Frequency – Inverse Document Frequency (TFIDF), and dimensionally reduced using Non-negative Matrix Factorization (NMF). A set of internal validation criteria revealed an optimal of five clusters among reviews tiered into the low (one to two stars), medium (three stars), and high-star (four to five star) ratings.

Based on the results of the NMF clustering of bigram vectorization of reviews, the five clusters reveal themes coherently associated with Customer Satisfaction: product descriptions, product quality, value for money, shipping time, and general feedback. The results of this study prove that with the use of unsupervised clustering methods, Amazon and other e-commerce platforms are given an opportunity to efficiently identify and take action on specific ailments customers may have within the transaction cycle.

  • Neutral Rated Reviews (3 Stars) = 13.3%
  • Low Rated Reviews (1 and 2 Stars) = 7.3%

Visual inspection show reviews pertaining to unfavorable reviews generally have longer words per review compared to favorable entries.

B. Data Pre-processing¶

An initial wordcloud is generated to visualize the raw data. Stopwords are removed to allow for more efficient use of the data by filtering out words with the least contextual significance. Special characters, non- informative tags, alphanumeric, and other unnecessary characters are removed from the data through regular expression (regex) search patterns. Customer reviews in the amazon.com platform employ the 5 star rating concept where products with low customer satsifaction rating are given 1 star, and products with high satisfaction rating are given 5. In this section, reviews are segmented according to the review ratings: High = 4 or 5 star reviews, Neutral = 3 star reviews, Low = 1 or 2 star reviews.

The processed output would be a used for subsequent EDA and vectorization that ensures compact, separated, balanced, and parsimonious clusters with more insightful results.

def decontracted(phrase):
    # specific
    phrase = re.sub(r"won't", "will not", phrase)
    phrase = re.sub(r"can\'t", "can not", phrase)

    # general
    phrase = re.sub(r"n\'t", " not", phrase)
    phrase = re.sub(r"\'re", " are", phrase)
    phrase = re.sub(r"\'s", " is", phrase)
    phrase = re.sub(r"\'d", " would", phrase)
    phrase = re.sub(r"\'ll", " will", phrase)
    phrase = re.sub(r"\'t", " not", phrase)
    phrase = re.sub(r"\'ve", " have", phrase)
    phrase = re.sub(r"\'m", " am", phrase)
    return phrase

def ngrams(review_list, n=1, top_n=10):
    """Determine the contiguous sequence of n words in a text.

    Determine n-gram strings per paragraph of the text and use them as
    keys with their counts as values. Sort the pairs first by frequency
    then alphabetically.

    Parameter
    ----------
    n : int
        Number of continuous words in a sequence.

    Returns
    -------
    ngrams_counts : dict
        Contains key-value pairs with n-grams as keys and their
        frequencies as values.
    """
    temp = []
    for review in review_list:
        words = review.split()
        if len(words) < n:
            continue
        start = 0
        end = n
        while end <= len(words):
            temp.append(' '.join(words[start:end]))
            start += 1
            end += 1
    temp = sorted(Counter(temp).items(),
                  key=lambda x: (-x[1], x[0]))
    ngrams_counts = dict(temp[:top_n])
    return ngrams_counts

1. Vector Space Representation¶

  • TF-IDF:

Term frequency-inverse document frequency is often used in information retrieval and text mining for converting text to a vector. It is considered as a marked improvement overt the traditional Bag of Words representation as it incorporates weights as a statistical measure used to evaluate the importance of a word in a document corpus. While the Tf increases as the frequency of words in the corpus increases, the IDF offsets this by giving more preference to the less frequent words.

  • Tf-idf Implementation:

Resulting Bigrams from the previous section are converted into the the Tf-idf vector, where word counts, inverse document frequency values are computed as well as Tf-idf scores.

2. Determination of Optimal Number of NMF Components and Clusters (k)¶

  • NMF

    NMF stands for non-negative matrix factorization, a technique used for obtaining low rank representation of matrices with zero or positive elements. NMF is specially useful for Topic Modeling and especially useful for clustering of text data where in it is helpful in finding meaningful patterns between words. Hence NMF has a distinctive edge over the traditional clustering methods such as Kmeans and Agglomerative Clustering.

    Given a data matrix A of m rows and n columns with each and every element $a_{ij} ≥ 0$, NMF outputs matrices W and H of size m rows and k columns, and k rows and n columns, respectively, such that $A≈WH,$ and every element of matrices W and H is either zero or positive. The quantity k is set by the user and is required to be equal or less than the smallest of m and n. The matrix W is generally called the dictionary or basis matrix, and H is known as expansion or coefficient matrix.

    The matrices W and H are minimized by calculating the Frobenius norm : $$ ||A-WH||^2$$

    Although NMF has already had many success stories in clustering, one challenge in the widespread use of NMF as a clustering method lie in its correctness. While dimension reduction and clustering are closely related, they have different goals and different cost functions to optimize. The goal of NMF is to approximate the original data points in a latent subspace, while the goal of clustering is to partition the data points into several clusters so that the intra-cluster distance is small and the inter-cluster distance is as large as possible. In order to use NMF as a clustering method in the right circumstances, we need to know first when the latent subspace corresponds well to the actual cluster structures. Another issue of using NMF as a clustering method is its time and space complexity, the Frobenius equation above suggests that finding the cost function is an np-hard problem and hence computationally expensive.

  • Choice of Parameter for K

The choice of the hyper-parameter K remains the single most important criteria for clustering. We have used a variety of internal - criterias for this purpose:

  1. Calinski-Harabasz Index:

    The Calinski-Harabasz index (𝐶𝐻) evaluates the cluster validity based on the average between- and withincluster sum of squares. It measures separation based on the maximum distance between cluster centers, and measures compactness based on the sum of distances between objects and their cluster center. $$s(K) = \frac{B(K)/(K-1)}{W(K)/(n-K)}$$

    where $B(K)$ is the between group dispersion matrix and $W(K)$is the within-cluster dispersion matrix defined by:

    $$B(K) = \sum_{k=1}^K n_k \lvert\lvert \bar x_k - \bar x \rvert\rvert_2^2,$$ $$W(K) = \sum_{k=1}^K \sum_{x \in C_k} \lvert\lvert x - \bar x_k \rvert\rvert_2^2,$$

    with $n$ be the number of points in our data, $C_k$ be the set of points in cluster $k$, $\bar x_k$ be the center of cluster $k$, $\bar x$ be the center of all points, $n_k$ be the number of points in cluster $k$ and $n$ be the number of points. The higher the value of this measure, the more defined the clusters are.

  1. Silhouette Coefficient:

    Let $Davg^{in}_i$ be the average distance of $x_i$ to data points within the cluster of $x_i$, and $Dmin^{out}_i$ be the smallest average distance to points other than its own cluster. The silhouette coefficient $S_i$ for the $i$th data point specific to the ith object, is as follows: $$ S_i = \frac{Dmin^{out}_i − Davg^{in}_i}{\max\{{Dmin^{out}_i}, Davg^{in}_i\}} $$ The overall silhouette coefficient is the average of $S_i$. Its value is in the the range (−1,1). Large positive values indicate highly separated clustering, and negative values are indicative of some level of “mixing” of data points from different clusters. This is because $Dmin^{out}_i$ will be less than $Davg^{in}_i$ only in cases where data point $x_i$ is closer to at least one other cluster than its own cluster. One advantage of this coefficient is that the absolute values provide a good intuitive feel of the quality of the clustering.

  1. Intra-Inter cluster Distance ratio:

    We sample $r$ pairs of data points from the underlying data. We then take the ratio of the average distance of pairs $P$ that belong to the same cluster, and the average distance of pairs $Q$ that belong to different clusters: $$ Intra/Inter = \frac{\sum_{(x_i, x_j) \in P)} Dist(x_i, x_j)/\left|P\right|}{\sum_{(x_i, x_j) \in Q)} Dist(x_i, x_j)/\left|Q\right|}. $$ Small values of this measure indicate better clustering behavior.

In [17]:
def intra_to_inter(X, y, dist, r):
    """Compute intracluster to intercluster distance ratio
    
    Parameters
    ----------
    X : array
        Design matrix with each row corresponding to a point
    y : array
        Class label of each point
    dist : callable
        Distance between two points. It should accept two arrays, each 
        corresponding to the coordinates of each point
    r : integer
        Number of pairs to sample
        
    Returns
    -------
    ratio : float
        Intracluster to intercluster distance ratio
    """
    dist_P = []; dist_Q = []
    np.random.seed(2020)
    for i, j in np.random.randint(low=0, high=len(y), size=[r,2]):
        if i == j:
            continue
        elif y[i] == y[j]:
            dist_P.append(dist(X[i], X[j]))
        else:
            dist_Q.append(dist(X[i], X[j]))
    ratio = np.nan if len(dist_P)==0 else np.mean(dist_P)/np.mean(dist_Q) 
    return ratio

def k_test(rating, tfidf_matrix, k_max, k_spec):
    """Plot internal validation results at differet k number of clusters.
    
    Parameters
    ----------
    rating: str
        Amazon star ratings, {'Low', 'Neutral', 'High'}
    tfidf_matrix : csr_matrix
        Tf-idf-weighted document-term sparse matrix
    linkage matrix : np.array
        Condensed linkage distance matrix
    k_max : integer
        Maximum number of clusters to consider
    k_spec : integer
        Number of clusters to select
        
    Returns
    -------
    matplotlib.pylot.figure
        Internal Validation Plots of the Calinski-Harabasz Index, 
        Intracluster to Intercluster Distance Ratio, and
        Silhouette Coefficient
    """
    chs, iidrs, scs = ([], [], [])
    ks = range(2,k_max+1)
    for k in ks:
        nmf = NMF(n_components=k, solver="mu", random_state=1208)
        nmf_transform = nmf.fit_transform(tfidf_matrix)
        pred = nmf_transform.argmax(axis=1)
        chs.append(calinski_harabaz_score(tfidf_matrix.todense(), pred))
        iidrs.append(intra_to_inter(tfidf_matrix.todense(), pred, cosine, 200))
        scs.append(silhouette_score(tfidf_matrix, pred))
    
    fig, (ax0, ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(15, 5))
    ax0.plot(ks, chs, 'o-')
    ax0.set_ylabel('Calinski-Harabasz Index');
    ax0.set_xlabel('Number of Clusters')
    ax1.plot(ks, iidrs, 'o-')
    ax1.set_ylabel('Intra to Intercluster Distance Ratio')
    ax1.set_xlabel('Number of Clusters')
    ax2.plot(ks, scs, 'o-')
    ax2.set_ylabel('Silhouette Coefficient')
    ax2.set_xlabel('Number of Clusters')
    ax0.grid(True); ax1.grid(True); ax2.grid(True); plt.close()
    ax0.set_xlabel('Number of Clusters')
    fig.suptitle("{}-rated Reviews".format(rating), x=0, y=.95, 
                 horizontalalignment='left', verticalalignment='top', 
                 fontsize = 24)
    fig.tight_layout(rect=[0, 0, 1, 0.9])
    return fig

def k_test(rating, tfidf_matrix, k_max, k_spec):
    """Plot internal validation results at differet k number of clusters.
    
    Parameters
    ----------
    rating: str
        Amazon star ratings, {'Low', 'Neutral', 'High'}
    tfidf_matrix : csr_matrix
        Tf-idf-weighted document-term sparse matrix
    linkage matrix : np.array
        Condensed linkage distance matrix
    k_max : integer
        Maximum number of clusters to consider
    k_spec : integer
        Number of clusters to select
        
    Returns
    -------
    matplotlib.pylot.figure
        Internal Validation Plots of the Calinski-Harabasz Index, 
        Intracluster to Intercluster Distance Ratio, and
        Silhouette Coefficient
    """
    chs, iidrs, scs = ([], [], [])
    ks = range(2,k_max+1)
    for k in ks:
        nmf = NMF(n_components=k, solver="mu", random_state=1208)
        nmf_transform = nmf.fit_transform(tfidf_matrix)
        pred = nmf_transform.argmax(axis=1)
        chs.append(calinski_harabaz_score(tfidf_matrix.todense(), pred))
        iidrs.append(intra_to_inter(tfidf_matrix.todense(), pred, cosine, 200))
        scs.append(silhouette_score(tfidf_matrix, pred))
    
    validation = {
        'Calinski-Harabasz Index' : chs,
        'Intra to Intercluster Distance Ratio' : iidrs,
        'Silhouette Coefficient' : scs
    }
    
    fig, (ax1, ax2, ax3) = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(15, 5))
    for j, ax in zip(validation, (ax1, ax2, ax3)):
        ax.plot(ks, validation[j], 'o--')
        ax.set_ylabel(j);
        ax.set_xlabel('Number of Clusters')
        ax.grid(True)
        ax.axvline(5, linestyle='--', color='red')

    fig.suptitle("{}-rated Reviews".format(rating), x=0, y=.95, 
                 horizontalalignment='left', verticalalignment='top', 
                 fontsize = 20)
    fig.tight_layout(rect=[0, 0, 1, 0.9])
    plt.close()
    return fig

Note on the Choice of Clusters:¶

While the internal validation criteria help us to get the optimal number of clusters, in literature there is no hard and fast rule to meticulously follow them and the choice of K ultimately boils down as to for which K's our cluster make the most sense. Data Science is an art and the choice of K is certainly accentuates the above point. For this reason,quite a few number of iterations must be used before we finally settle down on our optimal value of K

3. Dimensionality Reduction using Optimal K Principal Components¶

Dimensionality Reduction: A typical machine learning data set is prone to many challenges and high number of features/dimensions is one of them. the coined term is "Curse of Dimensionality" is a notorious term in all of data science. Thus its in our best interest to try and reduce the dimensions of our data set without loosing substantial information. There is always a trade off between computational complexity vs the amount of information we wish to retain.

The most popular dimensionality reduction algorithms are:

  • Principal Component Analysis (PCA)
  • Singular Vector Dimensionality Reduction (SVD or Latent Semantic Analysis (LSA))
  • Non-negative Matrix factorization (NMF)

For our analysis we have chosen NMF as our dimensionality reduction algorithm.

NMF for Dimensionality Reduction: NMF as stated above stands for non-negative matrix factorization wherein given a data matrix A of m rows and n columns with each and every element $a_{ij} ≥ 0$, NMF outputs matrices W and H of size m rows and k columns, and k rows and n columns, respectively, such that $A≈WH,$ and every element of matrices W and H is either zero or positive.

In the preceding section we talked about using NMF for clustering but for any clustering workflow dimensionality reduction is of prime importance. NMF is both a dimensionlity reduction and a clustering algorithm. In our analysis we have used k=5 as our number of clusters as well as the number of dimensions of our data set.

V. Cluster Analysis: Hard Clustering into K Clusters¶

In the preceding section we choose K=5 as our ideal number of clusters based on the basis of set of internal validation criteria as well as our sense of judgment about the clusters. Next, for each of star ratings viz. neutral , low and high we have performed clustering operation for K=5 leading to the creation of 5 independent clusters for each of the above category.

To reiterate, we have used NMF as our clustering as well as dimensionality reduction algorithm. Hence we essentially have 5 clusters or 5 dimensions for each of the 3 star ratings.

cluster_labels = dict()

    labels = dict()
    for k in set(predict[i]):
        cluster = reviews[i][predict[i]==k]
        labels[k] = list(ngrams(cluster, 2, 1).keys())[0]
    cluster_labels[i] = labels

Discussion of the above results:


In the above section, we have clustered each of the 3 star ratings into 5 independent clusters. The most frequent words for each of the 5 clusters have been correspondingly plotted.


Low-rated Customers:


As seen from above, we have 5 clusters under this category and the most frequent bi-gram is printed out for each of the 5 clusters. It is specially important to note that each of our clusters within a star rating actually represents a customer and his specific requirements. For eg: Cluster 1 has "waste money" as the most frequent bi-gram highlighting the fact that this set of customer are price sensitive Cluster 4 : has "customer service" as the most frequent bi-gram suggesting that this set of customers value seamless customer service.


Neutral-rated Customers:


As seen from above, we have 5 clusters under this category and the most frequent bi-gram is printed out for each of the 5 clusters. It is interesting to note that we don't get clearly defined clusters under this category compared to our Low and High rated category. This result is expected since the  neutral rated customers will be reserved/diplomatic in their opinions about the product.


High-rated Customers:


As seen from above, we have 5 clusters under this category and the most frequent bi-gram is printed out for each of the 5 clusters. It is specially important to note that each of our clusters within a star rating actually represents a customer and his specific requirements. For eg: Cluster 1 and 2 focus on customers who value product quality,while cluster 3 are those customers who are price sensitive.















5. Visualization of Clusters¶
The clusters have been visualized using the T-SNE method:


T-SNE:


t-Distributed Stochastic Neighbor Embedding (t-SNE) is a state of the art technique to visualize the data in two dimensions. This is specially useful for non-linear data. It is important to understand that t-SNE is not a dimensionality reduction algorithm but just a visual aid for plotting in two dimensions. The time complexity of T-SNE is $O(n^2)$ hence it is computationally expensive


Plotting Clusters using t-SNE:


Based on the internal validation criteria viz. Calinski-Harabasz Index, Intra-Inter Cluster Distance and the  Silhouette score we selected number of clusters as 5.


While the internal validation criteria help us to get the optimal number of clusters, in literature there is no hard and fast rule to meticulously follow them and the choice of K ultimately boils down as to for which K's our cluster make the most sense. Data Science is an art and the choice of K is certainly accentuates the above point. For this reason,quite a few number of iterations must be used before we finally settle down on our optimal value of K


At this point I would like to highlight that our t-SNE plots show some intersection between the clusters. The reason for this is that since our data is highly non-linear any two-dimensional representation would not lead to immaculate visualizations showing separation between the clusters. Hence the reader is advised to keep these things in mind before proceeding to the next section

It may be seen that each cluster is comprised of descriptive words representative of a specific aspect regarding product quality, customer service, and customer satisfaction.
